                <head>434. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>At a meeting of the National Security Council on October 2, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen Dulles</persName> gave the following assessment of
                    recent developments in the Philippines: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“With respect to the election campaign in the Philippines, Mr. <persName
                                corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen Dulles</persName> pointed out that it was
                            heating up, with only five weeks to election day. The Nacionalista
                            candidate, <persName corresp="#p_GCP1">Garcia</persName>, still had the
                            inside track at the present time so far as we could judge. <persName
                                corresp="#p_GCP1">Garcia</persName>
                            <pb facs="0756" n="728" xml:id="pg_728"/>was an uninspiring candidate
                            and vulnerable to charges of corruption. Yulo, the candidate of the
                            Liberal Party, had proved something of a disappointment. Emerging as a
                            possible threat to <persName corresp="#p_GCP1">Garcia</persName> was the
                            third candidate, Manahan, who in some respects inherited the tradition
                            of <persName corresp="#p_MR1">Magsaysay</persName>. He may still have
                            some chance. In any event, the United States could work well with Yulo
                            or Manahan.” (Memorandum of discussion at the 338th meeting of the
                                <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> by <persName corresp="#p_GSE1"
                                >Gleason</persName>, October 3; <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                                >Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName>Whitman</persName> File,
                                <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Records)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
